{{Infobox planet | minorplanet = yes | background = #D6D6D6 | name = 916 America | image = | caption = | discovery_ref = <ref name="ssd_jpl">{{cite web | url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=916;orb=1 | title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser - 916 America (1915 S1) | accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> | discoverer = [[G. N. Neujmin]] | discovered = 7 August 1915 | mpc_name = (1915) S1 | alt_names = | named_after = [[United States of America]] | mp_category = | orbit_ref = <ref name="ssd_jpl" /> | epoch = 31 July 2016 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2457600.5) | aphelion = {{Convert|2.9247|AU|Gm|abbr=on|lk=on}} | perihelion = {{Convert|1.8037|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} | semimajor = {{Convert|2.3642|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} | eccentricity = 0.23706 | period = 3.64 [[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (1327.8 [[Julian year (astronomy)|d]]) | inclination = 11.093° | asc_node = 329.79° | mean_anomaly = 245.58[[Degree (angle)|°]] | arg_peri = 41.772° | mean_motion = {{Deg2DMS|0.27113|sup=ms}} / day | observation_arc = 92.21 yr (33681 days) | uncertainty = 0 | abs_magnitude = 11.4 | rotation = {{Convert|38|h|d|abbr=on|lk=on}} | albedo = {{val|0.0530|0.004}} | mean_radius = {{val|16.615|0.65}} [[Kilometre|km]] }}
'''916 America''' is a [[minor planet]] orbiting the [[Sun]] in the [[main belt]] between [[Mars]] and [[Jupiter]].
It was discovered on 7 August 1915 by the [[Russia]]n astronomer [[Grigory Nikolaevich Neujmin]] at [[Simeis]], [[Russian Empire]].<ref name="ssd_jpl" /> Originally designated '''916<sup>Σ</sup>I''', it was renamed '916 America' on 24 February 1923 after the Council of Astronomers at [[Pulkovo Observatory]] decided to commemorate "the friendly relations of the astronomical observatories and astronomers".<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1923PA.....31S.364. Asteroid (916) America] (1923). ''[[Popular Astronomy (US magazine)|Popular Astronomy]]'', volume 31, page 364.</ref> Another possible reason for the name was as a mark of appreciation for the help given during the 1921 Russian famine by the [[American Relief Administration]] under the later President [[Herbert Hoover]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Dictionary of Minor Planet Names | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KWrB1jPCa8AC&pg=RA1-PA82&lpg=RA1-PA82&dq=%22916+america%22 | first=Lutz D. | last= Schmadel | year=2003 | publisher=Springer | isbn=3-540-00238-3 | page=82}}</ref>
In 1986, assuming that the asteroid was of S-type and that it had a diameter of 15&nbsp;km, the rotational period was measured to be 38 hours.<ref name="1986_Dimartino">{{cite journal | bibcode=1986acm..proc...81D | title=A Photoelectric Program for Small and Unusual Asteroids | last=Dimartino | first=M. | journal=Asteroids, comets, meteors II; Proceedings of the International Meeting, Uppsala, Sweden, June 3–6, 1985. Uppsala, Sweden, Astronomiska Observatoriet | year=1986 | pages=81}}</ref> Observations by the [[IRAS|Infrared Astronomical Satellite]] have since shown that it has a diameter of 33.2±1.3&nbsp;km, with an [[absolute magnitude]] of 11.20 and an [[albedo]] of 0.053±0.004.<ref name="ssd_jpl" />
