{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Biblical Porn: Affect, Labor, and Pastor Mark Driscoll's Evangelical Empire | image = Biblical Porn.jpg | image_size = | border = | alt = | caption = | author = Jessica Johnson | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | release_number = | subject = Anthropology of Christianity | genre = Nonfiction | set_in = | publisher = [[Duke University Press]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = May, 2018 | english_pub_date = | published = | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = 978-0-8223-7136-6 | isbn_note = | oclc = 994569650 | dewey = | congress = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }} '''''Biblical Porn: Affect, Labor, and Pastor Mark Driscoll's Evangelical Empire''''' is a 2018 book by Jessica Johnson about the culture of [[Mars Hill Church]] under the leadership of [[Mark Driscoll]]. Johnson is an anthropologist at the [[University of Washington]] in Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anthropology.washington.edu/people/jessica-a-johnson|title=Jessica A. Johnson - Department of Anthropology - University of Washington|website=Anthropology.washington.edu|accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The book uses research techniques including interviews with church leaders and members during the existence of the church.<ref name=speakersforum>{{citation|title=The rise and fall of a Seattle megachurch through the eyes of an anthropologist|author=John O'Brien|work=Speaker's Forum|publisher=KUOW|location=Seattle|date=June 14, 2018|url=http://kuow.org/post/rise-and-fall-seattle-megachurch-through-eyes-anthropologist}}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' said it provided "seething critiques" of the male-focused, "[[muscular Christianity]]" espoused by the church but was "more an [[ethnography]] than a exposé of a megachurch's downfall".<ref>[https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-8223-7153-3 Nonfiction book review - Biblical Porn: Affect, Labor, and Pastor Mark Driscoll’s Evangelical Empire by Jessica Johnson], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', May 2018</ref> [[Foreword Reviews]] said it displayed "deep insight and an absence of judgment".<ref>{{cite web |title=Review of Biblical Porn |url=https://www.forewordreviews.com/reviews/biblical-porn/ |publisher=[[Foreword Reviews]] |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> A local Seattle review described it as a reminder of "[[Toxic masculinity|toxic Christian masculinity]]" during a largely forgotten episode that is "almost impossible now to describe ... to someone who is new to Seattle".<ref>Paul Constant, [http://www.seattlereviewofbooks.com/reviews/the-name-of-the-wicked-will-rot/ The name of the wicked will rot], ''Seattle Review of Books'', May 22, 2018</ref> The author herself described the Seattle area as "definitely not immune to any of this" despite Seattle's "image" as progressive and irreligious.<ref>[http://kuow.org/post/record-wednesday-may-23-2018 The Record], [[KUOW-FM|KUOW]] Seattle radio, May 23, 2018 (starts at 35:00)</ref>
