{{short description|A submarine mountain range on the northern margin of the Cayman Trough in the Caribbean Sea}}
The '''Cayman Ridge''' is a submarine [[mountain range]] on the northern margin of the [[Cayman Trough]] in the [[Caribbean Sea]]. It extends from the [[Sierra Maestra]] in the east to the [[Misteriosa Bank]] in the west, a distance of about {{nowrap|{{Convert|1500|km|mi|abbr=on}}}}. The Cayman Ridge also includes the [[Cayman Islands]].<ref name="AJ">{{cite web|url=http://academic.emporia.edu/aberjame/student/unruh1/webpage.html#Ridge|title=The Cayman Islands: A Geological View| date=2008-05-01|accessdate=2018-02-12}}</ref>

The ridge formed as an [[island arc]] when the Cayman Trough was the site of a [[subduction]] zone during the [[Paleocene]] and [[Eocene]] [[epoch (geology)|epochs]]. As the dynamics of the area changed, the subduction zone became a [[transform fault]] zone with a [[pull-apart basin]] during which time [[volcanism]] had dwindled along the entire length of the arc. The Cayman Ridge is now an inactive volcanic zone.<ref name="AJ"/>

