{{Caymans-stub}}
{{Caribbean-geo-stub}}

'''''Hedu''''' or '''''Hedu kä misi''''' (literally, "sky layer")  is the [[Ya̧nomamö]] [[heaven]] and in the Ya̧nomamö [[cosmos]] the second highest of four layers. The top face of ''Hedu'' is like the [[earth]] (''[[Hei kä misi]]'') in all ways, containing wildlife, plants and [[Horticulture|garden]]s, but instead of living humans the Ya̧nomamö believe it to be the residence of the dead.<ref>Chagnon, ''Ya̧nomamö'', p. 100.; Wilson et al., [http://encarta.msn.com/text_701509044___2/native_americans_of_middle_and_south_america.html "Native Americans"]. [https://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1257007701458191 Archived] 2009-10-31.</ref> The activities of humans in ''Hedu'', like the environment there, resembles life on earth in most respects, and the dead eat, hunt, copulate and practice [[witchcraft]], just as living people do.<ref>Chagnon, ''Ya̧nomamö'', p. 100.</ref>

The bottom face of ''Hedu'' is visible from the mortal ground. All celestial bodies, the sun and the moon, the planets and stars, are attached to it and on it chart a regular east to west path.<ref>Chagnon, ''Ya̧nomamö'', p. 101.</ref>

