{{Infobox protected area | name = Inagua National Park | iucn_category = | photo = | photo_width = | photo_caption = | map = Bahamas | map_caption = | map_width = | location = [[Inagua | Great Inagua]], [[The Bahamas]] | nearest_city = | coordinates = {{coords|21.082|-73.372|region:BS-IN|notes=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnt.bs/download-main.php?mode=download&catid=4&subid=41&id=78|title=National Parks - National Treasures|page=20|work=The Bahamas National Trust|accessdate=2011-09-18}}</ref>|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|220000|acre|km2|0}} | established = 1965 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[Bahamas National Trust]] | world_heritage_site = | url = http://bnt.bs/inagua-national-park/ | embedded = {{Designation list | embed = yes | designation1 = Ramsar | designation1_date = 7 February 1997 | designation1_number = 892<ref>{{Cite web|title=Inagua National Park|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/892|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}} }}
'''Inagua National Park''' is a [[national park]] on the island of [[Inagua | Great Inagua]] in [[The Bahamas]]. It was established in 1965 and has an area of {{convert|220000|acre|km2|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bnt.bs/inagua-national-park/|title=Inagua National Park|last=|first=|date=|publisher=|work=The Bahamas National Trust|accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref>
From as far back as 1904 there was rising concern about the West Indian flamingo populations. During the 1960s, the [[Bahamas National Trust]] formed the Inagua National Park, which is where the world's largest breeding colony of [[West Indian flamingo]]es can be found. Forty years ago this flamingo species made a comeback from the brink of extinction to a colony of over 50,000 birds. The park has contributed to increasing bird populations in nearby islands such as [[Mayaguana]], [[Acklins]], [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], [[Cuba]], and [[Andros, Bahamas|Andros]]. In 1997 the park was designated a wetland of international importance. It is also known as a bird watchers' paradise as it was designated an Important Bird Area.
The park encloses all of Lake Rosa, the largest salt-water lake in the Bahamas.
